{
  "text": "All studies have consistently found that combination therapy with TCZ plus a DMARD is more effective than placebo (at either the 4 mg/kg or 8 mg/kg dose) at improving the ACR50 and ACR70 (OR 3.79 ACR50, OR 5.94 ACR70 versus DMARD). [CITATION_1] TCZ at a dose of 8 mg/kg was shown to be more likely to lead to DAS28 remission (OR 10.6 versus DMARD) and a greater improvement in HAQ-DI scores, with no significant increase in SAEs. [CITATION_2] Additionally, combination therapy with TCZ plus MTX was found to reduce radiographic disease progression. [CITATION_3] A systematic review by Campbell et al specifically focused on the risk of AEs with TCZ, and found that there was an increased risk of all AEs in patients treated with combination therapy (TCZ 8 mg/kg plus MTX) (OR 1.53) versus MTX alone. [CITATION_4] This included an increased risk of infection (OR 1.3). However, no significant difference in SAEs was seen even in the higher TCZ dose group. Due to differences in reporting of lipid abnormalities and neutropenia across different trials these AEs could not be evaluated. [CITATION_5] In general, the incidence of SAEs were low (1.5 events/100 patient years), but were increased further when TCZ was given in combination with a nonbiologic DMARD (3.6 events/100 patient years).",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "207667258",
    "[CITATION_2]": "207667258",
    "[CITATION_3]": "207667258",
